tsc

display the version

    tsc --version

tsconfig.json

The presence of a tsconfig.json file in a directory indicates that the directory is the root of a TypeScript project.

If tsc is launched with no input file, it will look for tsconfig.json or jsconfig.json.

      jsconfig.json is for JavaScript projects, it is the same as jsconfig.json except for some JavaScript-related compiler flags enabled by default.

If tsc is launched with some arguments, it will compile the files with the default compiler settings.

      tsc can be invoked with --project/-p to specify the path of a directory containing a tsconfig.json file or the path to a valid .json file containing the configurations.

generate the default tsconfig.json

      tsc --init
  



Duck typing

It is possible to pass parameters having a type that is a superset of the expected type

  interface Point1D {

  x: number;

  }

  interface Point2D {

  x: number;

  y: number;

  }

  interface Point3D {

  x: number;

  y: number;

  z: number;

  }

  const point1D: Point1D = { x: 0 }

  const point2D: Point2D = { x: 0, y: 10 }

  const point3D: Point3D = { x: 0, y: 10, z: 20 }

  function iTakePoint2D(point: Point2D) { /* do something */ }

  iTakePoint2D(point2D); // OK

  iTakePoint2D(point3D); // OK

  iTakePoint2D(point1D); // KO y is missing



Postfix !: Non-null Assertion Operator

The ! postfix operator removes null and undefined from a type without doing any checking.
function liveDangerously(x?: number | undefined) {

  console.log(x!.toFixed());

  }


Equality

== test equality with type coercition

=== test equality without type coercition

do not use ==, except for testing for null or undefined

to test if a variable is defined at the global level, use if (typeof someglobal !== 'undefined') { … }



for … of

An object is iterable if it has an implementation for the Symbol.iterator property.
Some built-in types like Array, Map, Set, String, Int32Array, Uint32Array… have their Symbol.iterator property already implemented.
Symbol.iterator function on an object is responsible for returning the list of values to iterate on.



for … in

for … in loops on the properties of an object.



Executing scripts

To run a TypeScript script using node, you can use ts-nodehttps://typestrong.org/ts-node/
enHTML:

npx ts-node --compilerOptions '{"module":"CommonJS"}' test.ts
